ce:section.ce:para:
Since the pioneering attempt on layered double hydroxides (LDHs) for CO2 photoreduction [10], LDHs have attracted considerable attention due to their layered nanoporous architecture, versatile composition, narrow/tunable band gap (from ultraviolet to visible region), high CO2 adsorption capability, low-cost and readily availability [11–13]. Up to now, multifarious LDH-based photocatalysts constructed from different modification strategies (metal loading, heteroatom doping, construction of heterojunction with a second semiconductor, and so on) with significantly boosted photoelectric properties have been applied to reduce CO2 with some exciting achievements (too many examples to be listed in 
                        Reference
                     ) [14–20]. Albeit these progress, it is still highly desired and pressing to develop facile yet effective recipes for further unleashing the potential of LDHs with more efficient activity release for CO2 reduction.
